item.title: Proc-9177285: Research Seed Multiplication Program - Secondary Site
item.description:
The Research Seed Multiplication Program has been developed to enable the success and return on investment for many high-value GRDC research investments. These investments rely on the sourcing of high-quality seed to achieve project outcomes.

The Research Seed Multiplication Program will ensure consistent delivery of seed of commercial varieties of wheat, barley, durum, oat, chickpea, lentil, lupin, faba bean and field pea to various research projects across Australia in a timely manner.

The aim of the project is to provide multiple secondary sources of seed for GRDC research investments, including NVT, to build redundancy into the program and assist in mitigating the risks associated with a single site and Service Provider.

The project will require reliable production sites, situated in appropriate geographic regions, to minimise risk of crop failure. Sites will contain all open-pollinated commercial varieties required nationally for the NVT project that year and will be used to provide seed to NVT Service Providers and GRDC researchers, along with surplus seed being retained into cold storage as a backup seed source in case of subsequent season failure.

This procurement will source, through an open market approach, a Service Provider who has the appropriate technical skills and experience to deliver the project outcomes.

item.title: PROC-9177339: Understanding GRDC's opportunities to leverage existing data repositories and facilitate data aggregation
item.description: GRDC’s strategy for RD&E data management focuses on improving the visibility and accessibility of its data assets by leveraging distributed data storage repositories that meet GRDC criteria (approved repositories GRDC also recognises that there are other repositories that specialise in specific scientific domains, such as AusPestCheck and the Atlas of Living Australia for pest monitoring data or NCBI for genetics research. These repositories enhance data interoperability and aggregation opportunities through standardised metadata and formatting. However, GRDC lacks a comprehensive understanding of the extent to which these repositories are used by research partners, whether they align with GRDC’s Criteria for Approved Repositories and how they may facilitate interoperability. This consultancy will assess existing data platforms and repositories, ensuring that GRDC adopts an effective and sustainable data aggregation strategy that supports interoperability across research domains.

The data service must be delivered through either a desktop browser, a secure online platform, terminal access across multiple locations and/or an API with sufficient functionality to meet the needs of geographically dispersed officers within DISR.

item.description:
This project seeks to generate targeted information to support decision-making by assessment officers and project proponents under the Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999 (EPBC Act).  

The research will investigate risks and potential impact pathways to little penguins (Eudyptula minor) arising from offshore wind farms and associated port developments in Australia. The findings will inform effective mitigation and management strategies, enabling regulators and industry to assess renewable energy projects under the EPBC Act with greater speed and scientific rigour.
